"The hush fell like a curtain’s edge as Carter slipped through the ornate double doors of the theater. Light from the lobby, cold and steel-gray, refracted in the glass turrets overhead. Around him, the murmurs of the crowd swelled—a tide of rustling programs, soft coughs, and the faint scent of roasted nuts. He moved with the crowd’s current, not quite among them, observing the careful choreography of their anticipation.\n\nOnstage, the dimness deepened, colored only by the ghostly silver of a single spotlight. Dancers in white, their lines precise as drawn plumb lines, began a reverent adagio from the first act. Carter watched the arch of a leg, the controlled tension in the neck and spine. Each movement told an ancient story—one of discipline, of beauty carved from struggle. The silence in the hall was so complete he could hear the scrape of a pointe shoe on wood.\n\nHe felt an odd kinship, not with the dancers’ bodies but with the centuries they embodied. There was a sorrow in the way the ballerina’s hands trembled at the end of a phrase, her eyes glimmering with unshed tears. The music was lush, aching, but nothing broken; the tragedy lay not in the performance, but in the awareness of impermanence. Every step was fleeting, a memory already softening at the edges.\n\nHe recognized her—$entity_1—the principal dancer, a woman so sculpted and silent that even the breath of the audience seemed to stop. He had spent the evening talking with others about the arc of ballet’s development, tracing its roots through Russia’s frostbitten courts, through Parisian revolutionaries, and through American reinventions. His words had drifted somewhere between the wine and the hush. Now, here, the past felt alive, breathing beneath polished soles.\n\nOctober’s wind rattled the iron railings beyond the theatre windows. The world outside was slick with early evening rain, but within, the air was sealed tight—a sanctuary of gaslight and music. Carter watched as $entity_2, a fellow attendee in a deep green coat, shifted restlessly beside him, her gaze flicking between the stage and the empty seats. She glanced over, but he offered her no reply; only distance lay between them, as inevitable as the next note in the music.\n\nPort Jefferson curled around the venue like a shadow cast at dusk, its steep cliffs visible even through the thick glass. In"